# LazySitter for Cursor

Cursor has the SAME structure as the Claude Code install:

- **Per-agent definitions**: `.cursor/agents/lazysitter-*.md` (26 agents). Each file pins its
  own `model:` and `readonly:` scope. Spawn them with the `Task` tool by `subagent_type`.
- **Orchestrator command**: `.cursor/commands/lsi.md` → run `/lsi <feature request>`.
- **Runs / audit trail**: `.cursor/lazysitter/runs/<slug>/`.
- **Kill switch**: `.cursor/lazysitter/KILL`.

When the user asks to **run LazySitter**, **run the autonomous engineering team**, or drive a
feature through the full intake → design → build → verify → release pipeline, follow
`.cursor/commands/lsi.md` as the orchestrator playbook and spawn the `.cursor/agents/`
subagents. Do NOT collapse it into a single-agent pass.

## Non-negotiable guarantees (same as Claude Code)

- **No agent verifies its own work.** Build lineage (implementers) and verification lineage
  (test-author, test-runner, code-reviewer, red-team, security-auditor) stay separate.
- **Tests come from the spec, blind to the code**: spawn `lazysitter-test-author` in parallel
  with the implementers from the frozen acceptance criteria; never show it implementation.
- **Always run adversaries**: `lazysitter-devils-advocate`, `lazysitter-red-team`,
  `lazysitter-security-auditor`, `lazysitter-secrets-scanner`, `lazysitter-closing-loop-auditor`.
- **Run in parallel** where the pipeline says so (triage+explorer; implementers+test-author;
  the Tier-6 verifiers).
- **Gate from structured verdicts**, not prose. A `degraded:true` verdict or an OPEN observable
  concern means the gate is NOT clean. Never force-merge.
- **You are the only hub.** Cursor permits one level of nested spawning; LazySitter forbids it —
  no agent you spawn may spawn another.

## Model pinning (already baked into each agent file)

Each agent's model is set in its `.cursor/agents/*.md` frontmatter, resolved from
`.cursor/lazysitter/models.json`:

| Tier | Model | Agents |
|------|-------|--------|
| `high` | `claude-opus-4-8-thinking-high` | architect, security-expert, devils-advocate, security-auditor, closing-loop-auditor |
| `high_alt` (distinct) | `gpt-5.3-codex` | red-team (must differ from the build lineage) |
| `mid` | `claude-sonnet-5-thinking-high` | spec-writer, experts, implementers, dependency-auditor, test-author, test-runner, code-reviewer, integration-checker, release/rollback |
| `low` | `composer-2.5-fast` | business-analyst-triage, triage, explorer, secrets-scanner, monitor, docs |

To change models, edit `.cursor/lazysitter/models.json` and run `lazysitter update` — do not
hand-edit individual agent files (update overwrites them).

## Cost controls you MUST apply

- **Spawn only what triage selects** (plus the never-skip verifiers) — no "nice to have" agents.
- **Cache verification**: run build/typecheck/tests once per commit and reuse the output.
- **Retry cap**: at most **3 auto-fix retries** total.
- **Mechanical retries only** may drop to the `low` model; never downgrade an adversary or a
  verification judgment.

## Usage contract

When the user says "run LazySitter" (or `/lsi`), respond by stating you'll run the pipeline, ask
clarifying questions ONLY for genuine business-scope ambiguity (or an imminent budget breach),
then proceed autonomously through the tiers.
